[normal]Overview[bold]General - Concerns of UK citizen[bold]s[bold] regarding the banking sector   [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The banking sector in general is
[normal] one which has been a source of concern to many, not least with regards to the unprecedented levels of sharp practice, deceptions and fraudulent behaviours of recent times, much of which has been documented by many, including politicians and media, and re 
[normal]which most, if not all, came to the attention of the UK and Northern Irish public, not through voluntary
[normal] disclosure and
[normal] transparency of the banks, but through the actions of others.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is the case that whistleblowing channels advised, or implied, by the b
[normal]anks via disingenuous published Corporate Social Responsibility Statements do not function as it is implied they do, a position which is indicative on one where the offender is also the ‘policing’ body, a position which for obvious reasons does not work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many cannot understand why regular laws which apply to the majority have not been seen to apply to those within the banking sector who set the corporate tone to which various deceptions and fraudulent behaviours (including bank officials providing inaccura
[normal]te information under oath, falsifying of documents, etc
[normal])
[normal], activities which at one time few would have thought banks would engage in, have prevailed, do not appear to apply to senior banking sector officials and executives, with questions asked by many as t
[normal]o why this may be.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many UK citizens remain confused as to why ‘ordinary persons’ are subject to stiff punishment for what are often fairly minor misdemeanours, whilst bankers responsible for hugely significant misdemeanours impacting upon every man, wo
[normal]man and child in UK, appear to have got off scot free, usually with huge financial packages of one sort or another intact, hedging those individuals from the negative impacts their behaviours helped to heap upon the majority of the nations citizens.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There
[normal] is evidence to suggest that operating principles possibly assumed to apply mainly to corporate tone setting senior banking executives may be more prevalent amongst some bank employees further down the corporate chain, as some employees, mindful of the sta
[normal]te of the economy and equally mindful of their own perceived job securities and future promotion prospects seek to consolidate their own positions via enthusiastic and compliant adherence to dubious operating principles and aims of the organisations which 
[normal]employ them.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There have even been new (and annoying) industries formed on the foundation of banking sector sharp practices, with for instance, millions of people frequently harassed by telephone callers, pre recorded voice messages and SMS text messages
[normal] relating to PPI, a sector which as stated, would not even exist had it not been for banking sharp practice on which it is founded. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given the events of the past few years, some feel there is justification for an independent body to be established where a
[normal]ll persons or organisations, not just from a customer perspective, but from all backgrounds where direct and negative impact has been encountered as a result of banking sector sharp practices
[normal],
[normal] and where any party who feels such sharp practices should be ex
[normal]posed, can do so without fear of retribution brought about by any bank or combination of banks, or from any third party or parties engaged by any bank or banks in connection to same.     
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-------------------------------------------------------------
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The Banking structure in Northern Ireland[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Northern Ireland Affairs call for evidence into the banking structure in Northern Ireland is welcomed by many (as is the recently announced banking enquiry in the Republic of Ireland (ROI) to be held at futur
[normal]e dates, those dates as yet undecided).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The reason why ongoing or pending
[normal] 
[normal]banking enquiries across the island of Ireland may be considered to be of interest to citizens of Northern Ireland / United Kingdom is because in Northern Ireland (and
[normal] to a lesser degree
[normal] on mainland UK) two of the Irish pillar banks are significant players, those banks being Bank of Ireland and the AIB (Allied Irish Banks) owned First Trust Bank (AIB in UK), whilst the Royal Bank of Scotland owned Ulster Bank is a major
[normal] player across both jurisdictions of Northern Ireland and ROI .
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Of the 4 four 
[normal]‘big four’[bold] banks operating in Northern Ireland, one of them, Royal Bank of Scotland / Ulster Bank is 82% owned by the UK Taxpayer / UK Government following a circa £45 billion b
[normal]ail out in 2008, whilst following similar bailouts also in 2008 in ROI totalling circa €30billion, Bank of Ireland is partially owned by the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government and AIB, owner of First Trust Bank in Northern Ireland is moreorless in full ownershi
[normal]p of the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In Northern Ireland, both ROI  banks, Bank of Ireland and First Trust Bank, are hugely influential in the banking affairs of Northern Ireland, are as Ulster Bank and Danske Bank (Northern Bank) a group of four whi
[normal]ch traditionally are recognised as 
[normal]‘the big four’[bold] in Northern Ireland banking, with one of the ROI banks, Bank of Ireland also additionally influential in NI and UK in connection to UK / NI Post Office savers via the fact that the bank is tied in with the 
[normal]Post Office
[normal] 
[normal](all NI and UK Post Office account holder statements are, unbeknown to many account holders, actually produced in Dublin, not in UK as many believe to be the case, with Post Office statements produced on Bank of Ireland premises and, in order t
[normal]o acquire a UK postmark on all envelopes bound for NI or UK Post Office account holders,  transported via road each day from Dublin to Belfast in order to acquire a UK postmark for every NI / UK bound envelope, delivered into the main UK Royal Mail postal 
[normal]facility for Northern Ireland at Mallusk, Co Antrim), a position which previously, for reasons known to the parties in question, some UK savers, UK taxpayers, UK politicians, relevant 
[normal]trade 
[normal]union officials, etc, queried or raised concerns.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Of the four ban
[normal]ks which make up ‘the big four’, in Northern Ireland
[normal],
[normal] only one bank therefore is actually UK owned, whilst as stated, two are ROI owned and one
[normal], Danske Bank,
[normal] Danish owned.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thus banking in Northern Ireland is hugely affected, and to a lesser degree re UK, 
[normal]by influences from outside of Northern Ireland / UK. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst there may be areas of general collaboration between banks within the UK banking sector, some understandable and acceptable perhaps, some not so i.e. Libor rate manipulations, etc, within the structure of the ‘big four’ banks in Northern Ireland ther
[normal]e appears to be areas and levels of collaboration, or collusion, which may not ordinarily be expected to prevail in any circumstances, but which not only do such collaborations and collusions prevail, connected to the position are elements of sharp and une
[normal]thical practices, and from which persons in Northern Ireland are victims of the practices referred to and from which the ‘big four’ 
[normal]NI 
[normal]banks unethically derive financial benefit. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These practices are referred to below under several sub headings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
