[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Purpose of the 2013 Northern Ireland Affairs Committee call for[bold] evidence[bold] on the banking structure in Northern Ireland Banking Enquiry[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The purpose of this enquiry is referred to in official parlia
[normal]mentary terms of gathering 
[normal]‘evidence on the banking structure in Northern Ireland’[bold], and referred to in other areas i.e. media sources such as BBC News
[normal] as
[normal] ‘a far reaching enquiry’[bold] and
[normal] [bold]‘[bold]NI banking practices under scrutiny’[bold], etc. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is no doubt that a number of areas require close attention, some of these areas very much focussed in the minds of the public, and thus unavoidable (which may be why the bank(s) concerned have referred to same within their published submissions to th
[normal]e NI Affairs Committee) i.e. the Ulster Bank IT debacles, rural and urban branch closures and the impact this has on those affected, etc.    
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, whilst volunteering information in relation to issues which the 4 NI banks are unable to influence the committee in terms of whether those issues are to be discussed or otherwise, there are areas of concern re which it is noted that none of the NI
[normal] banks have made any reference to but which nevertheless need to be addressed, possibly by a body as influential as the NI Affairs Committee. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Despite implied principles in Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements and in other areas, banks are not kno
[normal]wn for their ‘openness and transparency’, with the general public becoming aware of most, if not all banking misdemeanours not as stated previously through well meaning and ethically minded disclosure by the banks, but through the efforts of others.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I sug
[normal]gest that it is important that the NI Affairs Committee looks not only at those issues which the ‘big four’ NI banks refer to within their submissions to the Committee, the published submissions covering what most observers would have expected from the ban
[normal]ks, but as is the case in investigative procedures, often it is what isn’t voluntarily referenced which requires some element of investigation.      
